ass="wp-volt-gal-interstitial-text">Wait 1 second to continue.</div> </div> </div> <style>.wp-volt-gal-preroll-video{width:100%;height:100%}</style> </div> </div> <script src="https://js.washingtonpost.com/video/resources/js/posttv/plugin.jquery.wp-preroll.min.js"></script> <script src="//js.washingtonpost.com/pb/gr/p/ssiSingle/rO609L1qgAmx7p/hi-pri-render.js?_=67fb1"></script> <script src="//js.washingtonpost.com/pb/gr/p/ssiSingle/rO609L1qgAmx7p/render.js?_=67fb1"></script> <script src="//js.washingtonpost.com/pb/gr/p/ssiSingle/rO609L1qgAmx7p/instance.js?_=67fb1"></script> </div> <p>He had just given a speech about wanting to do more bold and diverse work, he said — so it seemed appropriate somehow that he was able then to hand off his award to such a bold, diverse movie.</p> <p>There’s no need to spend any more time talking about what he did last night, Horowitz insisted.</p> <p>“That moment on stage was not about anything but moving the spotlight to where it should have rightfully been,” he said.</p> <p>Besides, what he did was all just part of the job.</p> <p>“In a crisis, [producers] are levelheaded and decisive, and I try to operate from a place of doing what’s right on a moment-to-moment basis,” he said. “There was a real breakdown of process, and setting it right was in my mind the only option.”</p> <p>“All I know is there was a moment when I knew and it needed to be corrected,” he added. “There was just so much confusion. I think people needed to see that piece of paper. There needed to be some real definitive clarity and truth in that moment.”</p> <p>During awards season, the “La La Land” and “Moonlight” producers became close. They’ve been on the road together since both of their movies screened at the Telluride Film Festival.</p> <p>“I said it last night, I’ll say it again: I love those guys,” Horowitz said. “This awards-circuit thing is a grind. It’s a real full-time job, but we’re spending a lot of time together. All those guys, I would call them friends, and it needed to be fixed for them, too, as much as anybody.”</p> <p channel="wp.com" class="interstitial-link"> <i> [<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2017/02/27/reactions-to-oscars-flub-disbelief-steve-harvey-jokes-and-election-night-metaphors/?utm_term=.37e76e9c7797">Reactions to Oscars flub: Disbelief, Steve Harvey jokes and election-night metaphors</a>] </i> </p> <p>Backstage, after one of the most shocking moments in Oscar history, “Moonlight” director Barry Jenkins told reporters that “the folks from ‘La La Land’ were so gracious. I can’t imagine being in their position and having to do that. … I wasn’t speechless because we won. I was speechless because I — it was so gracious of them to do that.”</p> <div class="inline-content inline-html"> <blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-width="500"> <p dir="ltr" lang="en">Jordan Horowitz. Wow. I'm slipping slowly into reflection, perspective. Much respect to that dude</p> <p>— Barry Jenkins (@BandryBarry) <a href="https://twitter.com/BandryBarry/status/836125484505190402">February 27, 2017</a></p></blockquote> <p><script async="" charset="utf-8" src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js"></script></p> </div> <div class="inline-content inline-html"> <blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-width="500"> <p dir="ltr" lang="en">Thank you, Barry. Congratulations and much love. ❤ <a href="https://t.co/BSwk9T6Si4">https://t.co/BSwk9T6Si4</a></p> <p>— Jordan Horowitz (@jehorowitz) <a href="https://twitter.com/jehorowitz/status/836151933358362624">February 27, 2017</a></p></blockquote> <p><script async="" charset="utf-8" src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js"></script></p> </div> <p>When Horowitz was a victor, he seemed like a nice-enough guy.</p> <p>But as a loser, he showed what a champion for truth looks like.</p> <div class="inline-content inline-gallery-embedded"> <link href="//js.washingtonpost.com/pb/gr/c/ssiSingle/rO609L1qgAmx7p/css/b0fa517a2c.css?_=0c4a1" rel="stylesheet"/> <link